<h2 id="jargon">jargon</h2>

<ul>
  <li>LiPo - Lithium-ion Polymer</li>
  <li>NiMH - Nickel-Metal Hydrid</li>
  <li>Discharge Rating</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="capacity">Capacity</h3>

<p>Capacity is denonted in milliampers hours (mAh) on the battery. It is the amount of charge stored
in the battery.
If you have a battery with a capaciy 1 mAh and a motor is drawing 1 mAh then your motor will run for 1 h. In general the \textit{approximate} duration of a battery can be computed
by:</p>

\[\mathrm{duration} (h) = \frac{\mathrm{capaciy(mAh)}}{\mathrm{load (mA)} }\]

<p>If you have a 4700 mAh battery and it is powering a moter with a 100 mA load, it will
keep runing for approximatly 47 hours. <a href="https://electronics.stackexchange.com/questions/79279/does-mah-measure-how-long-a-battery-would-last">reference</a></p>

<h3 id="discharge">Discharge</h3>

<h3 id="battery-bank">Battery bank</h3>

<p>Combination of multiple batteries <a href="https://www.batterystuff.com/kb/articles/battery-articles/battery-bank-tutorial.html">reference</a></p>

<ul>
  <li>joined in series: voltage increases, capacity remains the same.</li>
  <li>joined in parallel: voltage remains the same, capacity increases.</li>
  <li>series and parallel: both voltage and capacity increase.</li>
</ul>

<p><a href="http://web.mit.edu/evt/summary_battery_specifications.pdf">A guide to understanding battery specifications</a></p>

<p><a href="http://www.ebay.co.uk/gds/RC-Lipo-Batteries-Buying-Usage-and-Storage-Basic-Guide-/10000000205584236/g.html">RC battery guide</a></p>

